For the sake of the challenge, if **absolutely no string manipulation methods or operators** can be used, one could theoretically use a loop to "manually" concatenate by iterating through each character and appending to a new "string" (stored as an array, then implicitly joined by the console or output method):

```javascript
var str1 = "Hello";
var str2 = "World";
var result = [];

for (var i = 0; i < str1.length; i++) {
  result.push(str1[i]);
}
for (var i = 0; i < str2.length; i++) {
  result.push(str2[i]);
}

console.log(result.join("")); // Outputs: "HelloWorld"
```

